 one that both reflects the American national interest but also can be said to have established the major security, economic, organisational and normative pillars of our epoch. In addition it provides excellent background reading for the current debate about American foreign policy and the origins of ‘neo-conservatism’ in international relations. This edition updates a very successful first edition of the title, with additional material to take into account changes in the global order since 2001 and the beginning of the ‘War on Terror’.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInternational relationsxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld politicsy20th century. 4aInternational Relations 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aAllied relationships.  aAnglo-American new world order.  aFirst World War.  aGeorge W. Bush.  aLeague of Nations.  aSecond World War.  aTheodore Roosevelt.  aTreaty of Versailles.  aVersailles Conference.  aglobal security.1 aWilliams, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978071909513940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780719095139423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780719095139/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles